    "type": "message",
    "text": "<@U7C7B75R6> Hmm.  Conventional shell CLIs combine several features that can be tweaked independently.  Part of it is that you have a dialog, a transcript of the dialog, the size of the exchanges in the dialog (commands and outputs).  Another part is representation (concrete and abstract).  Concretely, CLIs are text heavy if not text exclusive.  (Of course you have have a text-based UI that isn't a CLI <https://appliedgo.net/tui/.>)  And there is a question about how readily to can get at the text that you see on the screen.",
